	 <bioghist> 
		<head>Historical or Biographical Note</head>
		<note><p>The historical or biographical note provides background information about the creator of the material. It does not indicate the contents of the collection. Description of collection contents are found in the Collection and Series level Scope and Contents notes.</p></note>
		<p>Arthur Whiting Leighton (March 7, 1894 - March 5, 1973).  Arthur W. Leighton (AWL) taught engineering design at Tufts for over 45 years (1917-1963).  He was known for his dedication to students.  AWL served as counselor for freshman and sophomore engineering students from 1931-1960 and as director of counseling for the College of Liberal Arts and Jackson College from 1936-1948.  From 1944-1946, he served as director of the Veteran's Center at the Tufts School for War Veterans.  During his life, AWL was active in various Congregational church organizations.  </p>
<p>AWL served as an instructor of technical design at the University of Maine (1914-1917), as an instructor of technical drawing at Tufts (1917-1919), and as a mathematics teacher at the Huntington School (1921-1922).  He received his B.S. from the University of Massachusetts in 1921, his Ed. M. from Harvard in 1924, and his Ed. D. from Harvard in 1932.  AWL was married to Frances Rowland Freeman, and they had one son, Arthur W. Leighton, Jr.
</p> 
	 </bioghist> 
